      </div>
      <div class="pure-u-1-2">
        <div class="description description-right">
          <h2>Melbourne Metro Region</h2>
          <p>The Melbourne metropolitan region has generally reported lower bullying rates than across the state,
            despite
            having a range of NAPLAN scores (see above). This may be due to a variety of factors as any factor that
            attracts
            families to the city could be an explanation. Some possible examples are the parents education and
            profession,
            the funding of the school in question, or even the immigration status of students.
          </p>
          <p>
            Within metropolitan Melbourne, KNOX reported the most bullying in 2016 at 22.6%, and Stonnington the least
            at 6%.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <!-- end pure grid group -->

    <!-- pure grid group -->
    <div class="pure-g">
      <div class="pure-u-1-2">
        <div class="description description-right">
          <h2>Decline in Bullying</h2>
          <p>Finally, inspecting the nine most populous LGAs, we find that there has been substantial improvement across
            the years.
            Across all nine LGAs, less than one in five students report having experienced bullying recently, a
            significant improvement. </p>
          <p>
            Melbourne, in particular, has always had low bullying numbers, but has since been joined by Monash; both at
            one student in every eight.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
